ure that stretch credibility. More than a straightforward narrative of travel, the book has the ideological goal of attacking the corruption of Old World civilization and contrasting it with a vision of harmony, abdundance, and democracy resulting from the American revolution. The work has not previously been translated into English. \u003cbr\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.5772555\"\u003eView on Fulcrum platform.\u003c\/a\u003e\u003c\/div\u003e","identifier":"https://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.5772555","language":"eng","modified":"2025-08-14T08:22:07Z","published":"1964-01-01","publisher":"University of Michigan Press"},"links":[{"rel":"self","href":"https://www.fulcrum.org/ebooks/dv13zx444/download","type":"application/epub+zip"},{"rel":"http://opds-spec.org/acquisition/open-access","href":"https://www.fulcrum.org/ebooks/dv13zx444/download","type":"application/epub+zip"},{"rel":"http://opds-spec.org/acquisition/open-access","href":"https://www.fulcrum.org/ebooks/0v8383883/download","type":"application/pdf"}],"images":[{"href":"https://www.fulcrum.org//image-service/k3569791k/full/full/0/default.jpg","type":"image/jpeg"},{"href":"https://www.fulcrum.org//image-service/k3569791k/full/200,/0/default.jpg","width":200,"type":"image/jpeg"},{"href":"https://www.fulcrum.org//image-service/k3569791k/full/400,/0/default.jpg","width":400,"type":"image/jpeg"},{"href":"https://www.fulcrum.org//image-service/k3569791k/full/800,/0/default.jpg","width":800,"type":"image/jpeg"}]},{"metadata":{"@type":"http://schema.org/EBook","title":"The Hopi Indians of Old Oraibi: Change and Continuity","author":"Titiev, Mischa","description":"\u003cdiv\u003eFrom August of 1933 to March 1933, Mischa Titiev lived among the Hopi Indians of Old Oraibi, an ancient pueblo of the Hopi Indian Reservation in northeastern Arizona. A trained anthropologist, Dr. Titiev was adopted into the tribe and into the Sun clan during his stay - evidence enough of his remarkable acceptance by the people whose life he shared even as he sympathetically observed their ways. Subsequently, Titiev made return trips to Old Oraibi over a period of four decades, observing both the changes in the individual lives of those he had known and the signs of cultural change in the community. This fascinating diary of his extended 1933-34 visit - now published for the first time, and incorporating the observations made during the author\u0026#39;s many subsequent stays - thus stands as a unique and irreplaceable record of Hopi life, and a rare longitudinal study of sociocultural change.\u003cbr\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.5774110\"\u003eView on Fulcrum platform.\u003c\/a\u003e\u003c\/div\u003e","identifier":"https://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.5774110","language":"eng","modified":"2025-08-13T08:25:41Z","published":"1972-01-01","publisher":"University of Michigan Press"},"links":[{"rel":"self","href":"https://www.fulcrum.org/ebooks/ww72bf58h/download","type":"application/epub+zip"},{"rel":"http://opds-spec.org/acquisition/open-access","href":"https://www.fulcrum.org/ebooks/ww72bf58h/download","type":"application/epub+zip"},{"rel":"http://opds-spec.org/acquisition/open-access","href":"https://www.fulcrum.org/ebooks/6t053k38h/download","type":"application/pdf"}],"images":[{"href":"https://www.fulcrum.org//image-service/1544bs29s/full/full/0/default.jpg","type":"image/jpeg"},{"href":"https://www.fulcrum.org//image-service/1544bs29s/full/200,/0/default.jpg","width":200,"type":"image/jpeg"},{"href":"https://www.fulcrum.org//image-service/1544bs29s/full/400,/0/default.jpg","width":400,"type":"image/jpeg"},{"href":"https://www.fulcrum.org//image-service/1544bs29s/full/800,/0/default.jpg","width":800,"type":"image/jpeg"}]},{"metadata":{"@type":"http://schema.org/EBook","title":"Language and Art in the Navajo Universe","author":"Witherspoon, Gary","description":"\u003cdiv\u003eThis is a complex and theoretical study on the roles of language and art in Navajo culture, resulting from nearly a decade of research on the Navajo reservation. The structures of Navajo thought, language, speech, and knowledge are used to frame discussions on a number of topics. Primary among these from a cosmological perspective are the concepts of inner and outer forms in the duality on nature coupled with static and dynamic concepts of motion. Also explored is the importance of language in ritual control and perceptions of action, causality, and plurality. Two terms essential to the Navajo ethos are semantically explored as organizing principles. The first is the concept of k\u0026#39;T which finds its primary expression in the patterning of kin relationships and solidarity. The second is h=zh=, which is most easily glossed as representing Navajo ideals of harmony and order. Art examples, represented by music, sand painting, and weaving, are used to demonstrate how these complex semantic and cosmological considerations find their way into Navajo daily ritual life. Information is also included on color classification, numerology, mythology, ethnophysocology, and taxonomies. The conclusions expand the data into summary statements of Navajo ethos.\u003cbr\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.9705\"\u003eView on Fulcrum platform.\u003c\/a\u003e\u003c\/div\u003e","identifier":"https://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.9705","language":"eng","modified":"2025-08-13T08:25:40Z","published":"1977-01-01","publisher":"University of Michigan Press","subject":["Native American Studies","Anthropology"]},"links":[{"rel":"self","href":"https://www.fulcrum.org/ebooks/1v53k164c/download","type":"application/epub+zip"},{"rel":"http://opds-spec.org/acquisition/open-access","href":"https://www.fulcrum.org/ebooks/1v53k164c/download","type":"application/epub+zip"},{"rel":"http://opds-spec.org/acquisition/open-access","href":"https://www.fulcrum.org/ebooks/js956k04d/download","type":"application/pdf"}],"images":[{"href":"https://www.fulcrum.org//image-service/s1784p88n/full/full/0/default.j