llowing this is a consideration of gender identity as defined by Islamic law and by less normative sources like literature and mystical texts. It concludes by focusing on internal rebellions against the government of Muslim Spain, particularly the conflicts between Muslims who were ethnically Arab and those who were Berber or native Iberian, pointing to the limits of Muslim solidarity.\u003cBR /\u003e\u003cBR /\u003e Drawn from an unusually broad array of sources—including legal texts, religious polemic, chronicles, mystical texts, prose literature, and poetry, in both Arabic and Latin—many of Coope's illustrations of life in al-Andalus also reflect something of the larger medieval world. Further, some key questions about gender, ethnicity, and religious identity that concerned people in Muslim Spain—for example, women's status under Islamic law, or what it means to be a Muslim in different contexts and societies around the world—remain relevant today.\u003cBR /\u003e\u003cBR /\u003e\u003c\/DIV\u003e \u003cbr\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.9297351\"\u003eView on Fulcrum platform.\u003c\/a\u003e\u003c\/div\u003e","identifier":"https://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.9297351","language":"eng","modified":"2025-07-20T08:25:32Z","published":"2017-01-01","publisher":"University of Michigan Press","subject":["Medieval and Renaissance Studies","History:European History","Islamic Studies"]},"links":[{"rel":"self","href":"https://www.fulcrum.org/ebooks/v979v397g/download","type":"application/epub+zip"},{"rel":"http://opds-spec.org/acquisition/open-access","href":"https://www.fulcrum.org/ebooks/v979v397g/download","type":"application/epub+zip"},{"rel":"http://opds-spec.org/acquisition/open-access","href":"https://www.fulcrum.org/ebooks/ws859g993/download","type":"application/pdf"}],"images":[{"href":"https://www.fulcrum.org//image-service/ks65hd112/full/full/0/default.jpg","type":"image/jpeg"},{"href":"https://www.fulcrum.org//image-service/ks65hd112/full/200,/0/default